      "body" : "Okay, that's a very legitimate concern. Personally I have a 40 Mbps+ cable\nmodem connection and enable UPnP in order to serve the network. I can\nimagine lots of people, though, on much slower links, wondering why their\navailable bandwidth dropped after installing Bitcoin.\n\nAnd for nostalgia's sake, I'm also recalling those old limits built into\nconsumer versions of MS Windows, like <= 100 TCP connections open at a time\n:P\n\nOn Sat, Nov 19, 2011 at 12:47 AM, Matt Corallo <\nreply@reply.github.com\n> wrote:\n\n> There is a limit - currently 100 IIRC, though I would vote for the option\n> to change that in the GUI options menu.\n> Setting it lower is something that would have to be thoroughly discussed\n> first.  As I mentioned, the network is already starved of nodes which\n> accept incoming connections, limiting that number further could have very\n> serious consequences.  Someone needs to do some analysis of the network,\n> but until then, the max connection limit really shouldnt be touched IMO.\n>\n> ---\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub:\n> https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/issues/643#issuecomment-2796014\n>",
